SCENE VIII.                          MIRABELL, FAINALL, WITWOUD.  WIT.  That should be for two fasting strumpets, and a bawd troubled with wind.
Now you may know what the three are.
MIRA.  You are very free with your friendâs acquaintance.
WIT.  Ay, ay; friendship without freedom is as dull as love without enjoyment or wine without toasting: but to tell you a secret, these are trulls whom he allows coach-hire, and something more by the week, to call on him once a day at public places.
MIRA.  How!
WIT.  You shall see he wonât go to âem because thereâs no more company here to take notice of him.
Why, this is nothing to what he used to do:âbefore he found out this way, I have known him call for himselfâ
FAIN.  Call for himself?
What dost thou mean?
